	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>tepples</b> [ Fri May 08, 2015 3:34 pm ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Re: Hi-Def NES HDMI Adapter for the NES</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />The PPU puts out 262-scanline fields at a steady rate, and the TV likewise expects fields at a steady rate. These rates differ slightly. To make up the difference, the adapter stores a couple dozen lines of pixels in a circular buffer. But in order not to overrun this buffer, the percentage of the signal occupied by picture has to be within a few percent of each other. NTSC NES has 240 picture lines out of 262 signal lines, and HDMI 1080p has 1080 picture lines out of 1125 bitstream lines.<br /><br />960/1125 = 85.3 percent<br />240/262 = 91.6 percent<br />1080/1125 = 96.0 percent<br /><br />(.960 - .916)*262 = 12 lines of buffer<br />(.916 - .853)*262 = 17 lines of buffer<br /><br />Is 17 already too much?

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


